   "source": [
    "Chaining and Teeing - Lecture"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "72eb5c51-267b-47ec-9bd8-8f024eff1804",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Chaining Iterables\n",
    "\n",
    "itertools.chain(*args)\n",
    "-> lazy iterator\n",
    "Analogous to sequence concatenation, but not the same!\n",
    "-> dealing with iterables (including iterators)\n",
    "-> chaining is itself a lazy iterator\n",
    "\n",
    "We can manually chain iterables this way:\n",
    "iter 1, iter 2, iter 3\n",
    "\n",
    "for it in (iter1, iter2, iter3):\n",
    "    yield from it\n",
    "\n",
    "Or we can use chain as follows\n",
    "\n",
    "for item in chain(iter1, iter2, iter3)\n",
    "    print(item(\n",
    "\n",
    "Variable number of positional arguments and each item must be an iterable"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "c417bbfd-7374-4b3f-9fde-a892ca4d0d5c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Chaining Iterables\n",
    "\n",
    "What happens ifd we want to chain from iterables contained inside another single iterable?\n",
    "\n",
    "l = [iter1, iter2, iter3]\n",
    "chain(l) -> l\n",
    "\n",
    "What we really want is to chain iter1, iter2, iter3\n",
    "\n",
    "We can try unpacking: chain(*l)\n",
    "-> produces chained elements from iter1, iter2, iter3\n",
    "But unpacking is eager not lazy!\n",
    "\n",
    "If l was a lazy iterator we essentially iterated through l (not the sub iterators) just to unpack\n",
    "This could be a problem if we wanted the entire chaining process to be lazy"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "9a542192-8d65-4227-b0db-2bf4e2a229e1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Chaining Iterables\n",
    "\n",
    "itertools.chain.from_iterable(it) -> lazy iterator\n",
    "\n",
    "We could try this approach\n",
    "\n",
    "def chain_lazy(it):\n",
    "    for sub_it in it:\n",
    "        yield from sub_it\n",
    "\n",
    "Or we can use chain.from_iterable\n",
    "\n",
    "chain.from_iterable(it)\n",
    "\n",
    "This achieves the same result\n",
    "-> iterates lazily over it\n",
    "-> in turn, iterates lazily over each iterable in it"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "c90e6793-403d-4a9a-aaf6-218da1d6e081",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\"Copying\" Iterators\n",
    "\n",
    "itertools.tee(iterable, n)\n",
    "\n",
    "Sometimes we need to iterate through the same iterator multiple times, or even in parallel\n",
    "We could create the iterator multiple times manually\n",
    "\n",
    "iters = []\n",
    "for _ in range(10):\n",
    "    iters.append(create_iterator())\n",
    "\n",
    "Or we can use the tee in itertools\n",
    "-> returns independent iterators in a tuple\n",
    "\n",
    "tee(iterable, 10) -> (iter1, iter2, ..., iter10) {All different object}"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "0e37e9e6-e37e-4f0e-8c5d-930ab6827a4b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Teeing Iterables\n",
    "\n",
    "One important thing to note\n",
    "The elements of the returned tuple are lazy iterators, always, even if the original was not.\n",
    "\n",
    "l = [1, 2, 3, 4]\n",
    "tee(l, 3) -> (iter1, iter2, iter3) \n",
    "All lazy iterators not lists!"
   ]
  },
